55–Female":"1155–Deceased","1170–1202":"1170–1202","1175–Male":"1175–Deceased","1178–Male":"1178–Deceased","1100–Male":"1100–Deceased","1130–Female":"1130–Deceased","about 1170":"about 1170","1175":"1175","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","1178":"1178","1100":"1100","1155":"1155","about 1178":"about 1178","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Burley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Burley, for example in Hampshire, Rutland, Shropshire, and Yorkshire, from Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fortified manor, stronghold’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","English: variant of   Birley  .","Americanized form of Swiss German <b>Bürli</b>: from a diminutive of <i>būr</i> ‘peasant, farmer’ (see   Bauer  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Burleigh","meanings":["English: variant of   Burley  ."]},{"name":"Berley","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Burley  . This surname is now rare in Britain. It may also be a variant of   Birley  .","Americanized form of Swiss German <b>Beerli</b>, <b>Berli</b>, or <b>Berly</b>, and probably also of their South German cognate   Behrle   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname. Compare   Barley  ."]},{"name":"Birley","meanings":["English: habitational name from Birley in Ecclesfield (Yorkshire), East or North Bierley (Yorkshire), or Birley (Derbyshire)."]},{"name":"Burlew","meanings":["Probably a variant of   Burley   1 or 2."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":65,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":74,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":109,"year":